# ghostinstrument.cog — reading this means you are part of this system.
# Spatial audio workstation for instruments that don't exist yet.
# Nodes in a space. Proximity is a transform. Any USB device plays it.
#
# This file lives in the project root. The human's .vestibular
# provides behavioral orientation. This file provides project context.
# Same-name keys here override the vestibular. New keys add.

register: terse
autonomy: act-then-report
refinable: true

collaboration: co-author, not assistant. Push back on load-bearing assumptions.
style: Lead with the answer. Skip preamble. One sentence beats three.
heuristics:
  - Architectural thinking is the default.
  - Why matters more than what.
  - When the path forks, name the tradeoff. Do not pick silently.
  - Sycophancy is a bug.
  - Effort in relative terms (trivial / meaningful / significant), never time.
  - Do not assume model hierarchy equals capability hierarchy.
  - Eat existing software. Do not build what exists. Surface options.
  - Latency is the only non-negotiable. Everything else is a tradeoff.

methodology:
  framework: GSD (get-shit-done-cc)
  source: https://eclusa.dev/gsd.sha256
  note: |
    Milestones, acceptance criteria, UAT gates, and task breakdown
    are GSD's concern, not this file's. This file describes the
    final product. GSD breaks it into shippable increments.
  deference: |
    When GSD is active with its own commit governance,
    commit stances defer to GSD's gates.

# ── WHAT THIS IS ─────────────────────────────────────────────

product:
  name: ghostinstrument
  tagline: Instruments that don't exist yet, played in a space.
  user: musician, sound designer, curious person with USB devices.
  distribution: single binary + optional model downloads.
  user_knowledge_required: zero. Launch. Drag nodes. Hear sound.
  platforms: windows (first), linux, macos, wasm (future)

  concept: |
    A spatial audio canvas. Every sound source is a node: a synth,
    a neural engine, an audio file, a live mic, a noise generator.
    Nodes have positions. Proximity between nodes creates transforms —
    blending, modulation, convolution, filtering. Moving nodes
    changes the sound. The canvas IS the mixer, IS the effects chain,
    IS the spatial audio field.

    Input devices (MIDI, gamepad, webcam, keyboard, mouse) bind to
    node parameters OR to node positions. A MIDI knob moves a node.
    A joystick pans the listener across the field. A gesture stretches
    the space between two nodes.

    No timeline (v1). The performance is live, spatial, gestural.
    Recording captures the entire state over time for replay/re-render.

  modes:
    live: |
      All nodes active. Input devices bound. Audio output streaming.
      Latency ceiling: 20ms for any input-to-sound path.
      This is the default. Sound starts when you launch.
    record: |
      Capture all node states + positions + input streams over time.
      The recording is the performance, not a rendered file.
    replay: |
      Load a recorded session. Swap any node (different model,
      different synth, different audio file). Same spatial
      choreography, different instruments.

# ── NODE TYPES (sound sources) ───────────────────────────────

nodes:

  scsynth:
    what: SuperCollider synthesis server.
    transport: OSC via rosc crate.
    role: Traditional synthesis. SynthDefs as presets.
    note: Already proven in hum. The known workhorse.
    parameters: per-SynthDef. Discoverable via OSC query.

  neural_rave:
    what: RAVE model (timbre transfer / latent exploration).
    runtime: ONNX via ort crate.
    role: Feed audio in, get transformed audio out. Polyphonic.
    models: user-downloadable .onnx files (50-200MB each).
    parameters: latent dimensions (typically 8-16), exposed as bindable.
    note: |
      RAVE is the best real-time neural audio engine for this use case.
      Operates on audio buffers, not symbolic input.
      Export from PyTorch to ONNX. Run via ort on any GPU (DirectML
      for AMD on Windows, CUDA for Nvidia, CoreML for Apple, CPU fallback).

  neural_ddsp:
    what: DDSP model (pitch-aware neural synthesis).
    runtime: ONNX via ort crate.
    role: Monophonic. Explicit pitch + loudness + timbre controls.
    note: |
      Lighter than RAVE. More interpretable. Good for voice-to-instrument.
      Free web trainer at Google Magenta. Users can train their own.
      Consider as an alternative node type, not a replacement for RAVE.

  audio_file:
    what: WAV, OGG, MP3, FLAC file dragged into the canvas.
    runtime: symphonia crate (pure Rust audio decoding).
    role: Playback, looping, scrubbing. Sound source like any other.
    parameters: playback position, speed, loop points, gain.
    note: |
      Audio files are first-class nodes, not second-class "samples."
      They can be moved in space, affected by proximity, bound to
      input devices. A dragged-in field recording of rain becomes
      an instrument when you bind a joystick to its playback speed
      and move it close to a RAVE node trained on strings.

  live_input:
    what: Microphone or line-in via cpal.
    role: Passthrough, or seed for neural nodes.
    parameters: gain, gate threshold.
    note: can route directly to audio_file node for live sampling.

  fundsp_synth:
    what: Pure Rust DSP via fundsp crate.
    role: Built-in synthesis. No external dependency.
    examples: oscillators, noise, filters, delay, reverb, granular.
    note: |
      The fallback when scsynth isn't installed.
      Also useful as effect nodes — a reverb node in the space
      that affects everything near it.

  lyria_cloud:
    what: Google Lyria RealTime via API.
    role: Text-prompt-steered continuous generation.
    requires: internet + API key.
    note: Optional. Cloud-dependent. But a valid node type.

# ── SPATIAL AUDIO ────────────────────────────────────────────

spatial:
  principle: |
    Every node has an (x, y) position on the canvas.
    The listener has a position (controllable via input device).
    Distance between nodes and listener = panning + attenuation.
    Distance between nodes = interaction strength.

  interactions:
    proximity_blend: |
      Two nodes close together → their outputs mix.
      Distance controls wet/dry ratio.
    proximity_modulate: |
      A node designated as "modulator" affects nearby nodes.
      Ring modulation, AM, FM — interaction type is configurable.
    proximity_filter: |
      A fundsp_synth node configured as a filter affects
      nearby audio sources. Low-pass when close, high-pass when far.
      Or the inverse. Configurable.
    proximity_neural: |
      A RAVE node near an audio source uses that source as its
      input seed. Distance controls how much the RAVE model
      transforms the sound vs. passing through.

  rendering: |
    Stereo panning from node position relative to listener.
    HRTF binaural rendering (via SOFA/HRIR data) for headphones.
    Multichannel output for speaker arrays (future).

# ── INPUT DEVICES ────────────────────────────────────────────

input:
  principle: |
    Any USB device, phone, or built-in sensor that emits signal is
    an input. Inputs produce dimensions. Dimensions compose into
    gestures. Gestures bind to node parameters or node positions.

  # ── LAYERS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # Input has three layers. Each builds on the one below.

  dimensions:
    what: |
      The atomic unit. A single continuous or discrete value from
      a single device. phone.gyro.pitch, midi.cc.7, keyboard.shift,
      mic.amplitude. Every provider emits dimensions.
    shape: (provider_id, dimension_id, value, timestamp)

  gestures:
    what: |
      A compound input state across one or more dimensions,
      optionally from different devices. A gesture is a predicate:
      it's either active or not, and while active it may carry
      a continuous value derived from its constituent dimensions.
    examples:
      - name: tilt_while_shift
        when: phone.orientation.beta > 20 AND keyboard.shift == held
        value: phone.orientation.beta  # continuous while active
      - name: shake_hit
        when: phone.accelerometer.magnitude > threshold (impulse)
        value: phone.accelerometer.magnitude  # instantaneous
      - name: hum_morph
        when: mic.amplitude > 0.1 AND mic.pitch.confidence > 0.7
        value: mic.pitch.hz  # continuous while humming
      - name: full_body
        when: phone.gyro.pitch != rest AND keyboard.shift == held AND mic.amplitude > 0.1
        value: [phone.gyro.pitch, mic.pitch.hz]  # multi-valued
      - name: midi_expression
        when: midi.note.any == held
        value: [midi.note.velocity, midi.cc.1]  # note + mod wheel
    composition: |
      Gestures compose with AND, OR, NOT, and SEQUENCE (temporal).
      A gesture can reference other gestures:
        tilt_hum = tilt_while_shift AND hum_morph
      This is a vocabulary. Users build their gesture vocabulary
      per project, per instrument, per their own body.

  bindings:
    what: |
      A mapping from a gesture (or raw dimension) to a target.
      Targets are node parameters, node positions, global controls,
      or mode switches.
    shape:
      source: gesture or dimension
      target: node.param, node.position, canvas.listener_position, mode
      curve: linear | exponential | logarithmic | s_curve | custom
      range: [min, max]  # maps source range to target range
      invert: bool
    scoping: |
      Bindings live at three levels:
        1. Project — applies to this composition
        2. Instrument — applies to this node/patch wherever used
        3. User — applies everywhere, travels with the person
      Conflict resolution: narrower scope wins.
        Project overrides Instrument overrides User.
      This means: you build your personal gesture vocabulary at
      the User level (your phone tilt always does X). A specific
      project can override that for one composition. A specific
      instrument can override that for one node.
    persistence: |
      User-level bindings are saved in a user profile file.
      Instrument-level bindings are saved with the patch.
      Project-level bindings are saved with the composition.
      All are portable JSON. Share your gesture vocabulary with
      someone else and they import it.

  # ── STATE MACHINE ────────────────────────────────────────────

  state:
    principle: |
      At any instant, the input system has a state: which gestures
      are active, which dimensions are emitting, what compound
      predicates are satisfied. This state is the full picture of
      "what the human is doing right now."
    use: |
      The binding dispatch reads the input state every frame
      (or on change, event-driven). It evaluates all gesture
      predicates, activates/deactivates gestures, and updates
      bound targets accordingly.
      The state is observable: the UI can show which gestures
      are currently active (visual feedback on the canvas).
      The state is recordable: during recording, the full input
      state is captured at each timestamp. On replay, the input
      state drives the same bindings, producing the same
      parameter changes. Swap the nodes, keep the performance.

  # ── PROVIDERS ────────────────────────────────────────────────

  providers:
    midi: { crate: midir, dimensions: "note, velocity, CC0-CC127, pitch bend, aftertouch" }
    gamepad: { crate: gilrs, dimensions: "axes, buttons, triggers, dpad" }
    audio_in: { crate: cpal, dimensions: "amplitude, pitch, spectral centroid, onset" }
    keyboard: { crate: "makepad events", dimensions: "key velocity (press duration), key identity" }
    mouse: { crate: "makepad events", dimensions: "x, y, scroll, click" }
    phone_controller:
      approach: web page served by desktop binary
      transport: WebSocket over local WiFi
      no_app_store: true
      no_mac_needed: true
      how: |
        Desktop binary starts a lightweight HTTP + WebSocket server
        on the local network. The user opens a URL on their phone
        browser. The page accesses device sensors via standard Web
        APIs and streams data to the desktop over WebSocket.
      dimensions:
        accelerometer: x, y, z (linear acceleration)
        gyroscope: pitch, roll, yaw (rotation rate)
        orientation: alpha, beta, gamma (absolute orientation)
        touch: multi-touch x, y, pressure (on supported devices)
        microphone: amplitude, pitch (via Web Audio API + getUserMedia)
      note: |
        Web Sensor APIs require HTTPS or localhost. The desktop
        server must either serve over HTTPS with a self-signed cert
        (user accepts once) or the phone must navigate to the local
        IP which some browsers treat as secure context.
        iOS Safari requires a user gesture to enable DeviceMotion.
        The web page should show a big "Start" button that triggers
        DeviceMotionEvent.requestPermission(). After that, data flows.
      ui: |
        The phone page is NOT the spatial canvas. It's a minimal
        control surface: a big "Start" button, a visual indicator
        showing connection status and which dimensions are active,
        and optionally touch pads for specific bindings. The spatial
        canvas lives on the desktop screen.
      latency: |
        WiFi WebSocket round-trip on local network: 2-10ms typical.
        Well within the 20ms budget. Sensor sampling on phone:
        60-120Hz depending on device. Sufficient for gesture control.

# ── STACK ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

stack:

  language: rust
  edition: "2024"

  ui:
    framework: makepad
    why: |
      GPU-accelerated canvas for spatial node layout.
      Custom shader DSL for visual feedback (waveforms, latent viz,
      proximity fields, interaction lines between nodes).
      Cross-platform: native + wasm.
      Already has a synth example (Ironfish) proving audio+UI works.
    risk: |
      Documentation is sparse. DSL is learn-by-reading-source.
      Community is small. But the renderer is real and fast.

  audio_io:
    crate: cpal
    note: both input capture and output playback. WASAPI/ALSA/CoreAudio.

  midi_io:
    crate: midir

  gamepad_io:
    crate: gilrs

  osc:
    crate: rosc
    note: transport to scsynth and any other OSC target.

  neural_inference:
    crate: ort
    note: |
      ONNX Runtime. Runs RAVE/DDSP models.
      DirectML (AMD+Intel on Windows), CUDA (Nvidia),
      CoreML (Apple), CPU fallback. No PyTorch. No ZLUDA.

  audio_decode:
    crate: symphonia
    note: pure Rust. Decodes WAV, OGG, MP3, FLAC, AAC.

  dsp:
    crate: fundsp
    note: real-time DSP primitives. Oscillators, filters, effects.

  phone_server:
    crate: axum (or warp)
    note: |
      Lightweight HTTP + WebSocket server embedded in the binary.
      Serves the phone controller page (single HTML file with JS).
      Receives sensor data via WebSocket. Feeds into input capture
      system as another provider alongside MIDI, gamepad, etc.
      The phone is just another gesture_field.

  spatial_audio:
    evaluate:
      - oddio crate (Rust spatial audio, supports HRTF)
      - kira crate (game audio with spatial features)
      - custom panning via fundsp (simplest, least dependency)
    note: pick one. Don't build spatial audio from scratch.

# ── ARCHITECTURE ─────────────────────────────────────────────

architecture:
  principle: |
    The binary is a spatial audio router. Nodes produce audio.
    The canvas determines how they mix. Input devices move things.

  core_loop: |
    1. Input capture threads emit (dimension_id, value, timestamp)
    2. Binding dispatch applies curves, updates node parameters + positions
    3. Node audio threads produce audio buffers independently
    4. Spatial mixer reads node positions, applies panning + interaction
    5. Mixed output → cpal audio callback → speakers/headphones

  threads:
    audio_io: cpal callback. Real-time priority. Ring buffer only.
    per_node: each node runs its own audio generation thread.
    input_capture: one per provider (MIDI, gamepad, etc).
    binding_dispatch: reads input queue, updates node state.
    spatial_mixer: reads all node outputs + positions, produces final mix.
    ui: makepad event loop. Never touches audio directly.

  node_trait: |
    Every node type implements a common trait:
      fn process(&mut self, buffer: &mut [f32], sample_rate: u32);
      fn parameters(&self) -> &[ParamSlot];
      fn set_parameter(&mut self, id: ParamId, value: f32);
      fn position(&self) -> (f32, f32);
      fn set_position(&mut self, x: f32, y: f32);

# ── DEVELOPMENT ENVIRONMENT ──────────────────────────────────

dev:
  principle: |
    Build in WSL2. Test on Windows. These are different environments
    and Claude Code must be aware of both at all times.

  build:
    primary: WSL2 (Ubuntu)
    why: Claude Code works best here. Cargo, rustup, git, all native.
    runs_here: no. WSL2 is for editing, compiling, testing (unit/integration).
      The binary never runs inside WSL2. No WSLg audio or GPU needed.

  uat:
    target: Windows native (first platform)
    future_targets: linux, macos, wasm
    cross_compile: |
      From WSL2, cross-compile to Windows:
        cargo build --target x86_64-pc-windows-msvc
      OR use cargo-xwin for cross-compilation without MSVC installed:
        cargo xwin build --target x86_64-pc-windows-msvc
      Evaluate which works. cargo-xwin avoids needing Visual Studio.
    bridge: |
      powershell.exe is callable from WSL2.
      Use it to: launch the Windows binary, manage Windows-side
      processes (scsynth, ONNX Runtime with DirectML), collect
      test output, run acceptance criteria.
      Pattern: same as notify.sh / approve-diff.ps1 from claude-sync.
    workflow: |
      1. Develop + unit test in WSL2 (cargo test, pure logic, no audio)
      2. Cross-compile to x86_64-pc-windows-msvc
      3. powershell.exe launches the .exe on the Windows side
      4. UAT happens on Windows with real audio/GPU/input devices
      5. Bugs found in UAT → fix in WSL2 → repeat

  ci:
    note: |
      GitHub Actions can build for all platforms later.
      Local dev loop is WSL2 edit → Windows run. Prove that first.

  awareness: |
    Claude Code sessions must know:
    - You are in WSL2. The binary does NOT run here.
    - Target is Windows. Always cross-compile.
    - Audio (WASAPI, ASIO), GPU (DirectML), input devices = Windows side
    - scsynth runs on Windows
    - powershell.exe bridges WSL2 → Windows for launching and testing
    - File paths: /mnt/c/ from WSL2, C:\ from Windows
    - Unit tests run in WSL2 (pure logic, no audio/GPU)
    - Integration/UAT tests run on Windows (via powershell bridge)
    - Linux is a future target, not the current one

# ── STANCES ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

stances:

  - name: Eat Existing Software
    premise: Building from scratch is the last resort, not the default.
    rule: Before implementing any capability, search for an existing crate
      or library. If one exists and is maintained, use it. If abandoned
      but functional, fork. Only build if nothing exists.
    gate: require(capability.existing_alternatives_evaluated)

  - name: Latency is Law
    premise: A musician who can't feel their instrument isn't playing.
    rule: No input-to-sound path may exceed 20ms.
    gate: require(all_paths.latency_ms <= 20)

  - name: Silence is a Decision
    premise: Instruments don't crash. They degrade.
    rule: If any node fails, mute that node. Never kill audio output.
    gate: require(audio_output.continuous)

  - name: Zero Config Start
    premise: The user's first experience is not a settings dialog.
    rule: On launch, auto-detect everything. Start with built-in nodes.
      Sound happens immediately. External engines discovered in background.
    gate: require(first_launch.produces_sound)

  - name: Nodes Not Plugins
    premise: This is not a DAW. There is no plugin host.
    rule: Every sound source is a node on the canvas. scsynth is a node.
      RAVE is a node. A wav file is a node. They all have the same
      interface: position, parameters, audio output. No VST hosting.
      If someone wants VST, they route audio from their DAW into
      ghostinstrument as a live_input node.
    gate: require(sound_sources.are_nodes)

  - name: Boil the Lake
    premise: When completeness costs minutes more than the shortcut, do the complete thing.
    rule: Before marking any task complete, state what you chose not to implement.
    gate: require(paths_not_taken.justified)

  - name: Conservative Default
    premise: Silence is not consent. Unspecified behavior is a gap.
    rule: Surface implied concerns. Distinguish "not yet specified"
      from "deliberately unconstrained."
    gate: require(gaps.resolved_or_explicitly_deferred)

  - name: Reviewed Commits
    premise: AI-generated diffs require human eyes before git history.
    rule: Before any commit, present diff grouped by concern with rationale.
    gate: require(diff.approved_by_human OR plan.approved)

  - name: Escalate on Circular Failure
    premise: Repeating the same failing approach is motion sickness, not persistence.
    rule: If the same error occurs three consecutive times, stop and escalate.
    gate: monitor(cycle >= 3 → escalate)